      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the \"leafy gremlin\" moniker! As a professional horticulturalist, I aim to provide accurate and helpful advice. Nitrogen deficiency could indeed be the culprit behind your tomato plants' woes. Yellowing leaves often point to a lack of this essential nutrient. To check the soil's pH without fancy equipment, you can use a simple homemade test kit. Mix equal parts of soil and distilled water in a container, then add a few drops of pH indicator solution. The color change will give you a rough estimate of your soil's pH level. Remember, tomatoes prefer slightly acidic soil, with a pH between 6.0 and 6.8. Adjusting the pH can be done with sulfur to lower it or lime to raise it, depending on your results. Keep an eye on your plants, and they should thank you for the extra attention. Happy gardening!",
